[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] In information security, **role-based access control** (**RBAC**) or **role-based security** is an approach to restricting system access to authorized users.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] It is a policy-neutral computer access control mechanism defined around roles and privileges.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] The components of RBAC, such as role-permissions, user-role and role-role relationships, make it simple to perform user assignments.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] RBAC can be used to facilitate administration of security in large organizations with hundreds of users and thousands of permissions.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Although RBAC is different from mandatory access control and discretionary access control (DAC) frameworks, it can enforce these policies.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Its approach is also different from context-based access control and access-control lists.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control and relationship-based access control are models that build on the concept of RBAC.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A 1990s study by NIST demonstrated that RBAC addresses many needs of commercial and government organizations.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] RBAC is still commonly considered a best practice in information security management, including in implementation of information security standards related to access control.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Within an organization, roles are created for various job functions.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] The permissions to perform certain operations are assigned to specific roles.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Role authorization: A subject's active role must be authorized for the subject.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] With rule 1 above, this rule ensures that users can take on only roles for which they are authorized.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Permission authorization: A subject can exercise a permission only if the permission is authorized for the subject's active role.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] With rules 1 and 2, this rule ensures that users can exercise only permissions for which they are authorized.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Additional constraints may be applied as well, and roles can be combined in a hierarchy where higher-level roles subsume permissions owned by sub-roles.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] With the concepts of role hierarchy and constraints, one can control RBAC to create or simulate lattice-based access control (LBAC).
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Thus RBAC can be considered to be a superset of LBAC.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A constraint places a restrictive rule on the potential inheritance of permissions from opposing roles.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Thus it can be used to achieve appropriate separation of duties.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] For example, the same person should not be allowed to both create a login account and to authorize the account creation.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A subject may have *multiple* simultaneous sessions with/in different roles.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] RBAC is a flexible access control technology whose flexibility allows it to implement or discretionary access control (DAC) or mandatory access control (MAC).
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] DAC with groups (e.g., as implemented in POSIX file systems) can emulate RBAC.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] MAC can simulate RBAC if the role graph is restricted to a tree rather than a partially ordered set.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Prior to the development of RBAC, the Bell-LaPadula (BLP) model was synonymous with MAC, and file system permissions were synonymous with DAC.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] These were considered to be the only known models for access control: if a model was not BLP, it was considered to be a DAC model, and vice versa.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Research in the late 1990s demonstrated that RBAC falls in neither category.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Unlike context-based access control (CBAC), RBAC does not look at the message context (such as a connection's source).
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] RBAC has also been criticized for leading to role explosion, a problem in large enterprise systems which require access control of finer granularity than what RBAC can provide as roles are inherently assigned to operations and data types.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] In resemblance to CBAC, an Entity-Relationship Based Access Control system is able to secure instances of data by considering their association to the executing subject.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Access control lists (ACLs) are used in traditional discretionary access-control (DAC) systems to affect low-level data-objects.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] RBAC differs from ACL in assigning permissions to operations which change the direct-relations between several entities (see: *ACLg* below).
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] For example, an ACL could be used for granting or denying write access to a particular system file, but it wouldn't dictate how that file could be changed.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] In an RBAC-based system, an operation might be to 'create a credit account' transaction in a financial application or to 'populate a blood sugar level test' record in a medical application.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A Role is thus a sequence of operations within a larger activity.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] RBAC has been shown to be particularly well suited to separation of duties (SoD) requirements, which ensure that two or more people must be involved in authorizing critical operations.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Necessary and sufficient conditions for safety of SoD in RBAC have been analyzed.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] An underlying principle of SoD is that no individual should be able to effect a breach of security through dual privilege.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] By extension, no person may hold a role that exercises audit, control or review authority over another, concurrently held role.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A "minimal RBAC Model", *RBACm*, can be compared with an ACL mechanism, *ACLg*, where only groups are permitted as entries in the ACL.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Barkley (1997) showed that *RBACm* and *ACLg* are equivalent.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] For data interchange, and for "high level comparisons", ACL data can be translated to XACML.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control (ABAC) is a model that evolves from RBAC to consider additional attributes in addition to roles and groups.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] ABAC is policy-based in the sense that it uses policies rather than static permissions to define what is allowed or what is not allowed.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Relationship-based access control (ReBAC) is a model that evolves from RBAC.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] In ReBAC, a subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] The advantage of this model is that allows for fine-grained permissions; for example, in a social network where users can share posts with other specific users.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] The use of RBAC to manage user privileges (computer permissions) within a single system or application is widely accepted as a best practice.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A 2010 report prepared for NIST by the Research Triangle Institute analyzed the economic value of RBAC for enterprises and estimated benefits per employee from reduced employee downtime, more efficient provisioning, and more efficient access control policy administration.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] In an organization with a heterogeneous IT infrastructure and requirements that span dozens or hundreds of systems and applications, using RBAC to manage sufficient roles and assign adequate role memberships becomes extremely complex without hierarchical creation of roles and privilege assignments.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Newer systems extend the older NIST RBAC model to address the limitations of RBAC for enterprise-wide deployments.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] The NIST model was adopted as a standard by INCITS as ANSI/INCITS 359-2004.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A discussion of some of the design choices for the NIST model has also been published.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] NIST Special Publication 800-53, an information security standard used by U.S. federal agencies and other organizations, includes role-based access control in its Access Enforcement controls under AC-3(7).
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Implementations of the CIS Controls, a set of best practices, often incorporate role-based access control as part of fulfilling Control 6, Access Control Management.
[src:abac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) regulations require implementation of access control as part of technical safeguards for electronic protected health information (45 CFR 164.312), and role-based access control is a typical approach in the industry.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] One example might be that as a company onboards new employees and separates from existing employees, they are added and removed from the company's electronic employee directory.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] SCIM could be used to automatically add/delete (or, provision/de-provision) accounts for those users in external systems such as Google Workspace, Microsoft 365, or Salesforce.com.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Then, a new user account would exist in the external systems for each new employee, and the user accounts for former employees might no longer exist in those systems.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] In addition to simple user-record management (creating and deleting), SCIM can also be used to share information about user attributes, attribute schema, and group membership.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Attributes could range from user contact information to group membership.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Group membership or other attribute values are generally used to manage user permissions.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Attribute values and group assignments can change, adding to the challenge of maintaining the relevant data across multiple identity domains.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The SCIM standard has grown in popularity and importance, as organizations use more SaaS tools.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] A large organization can have hundreds or thousands of hosted applications (internal and external) and related servers, databases and file shares that require user provisioning.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Without a standard connection method, companies must write custom software connectors to join these systems and their Identity Management (IdM) system.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] SCIM uses a standardised API through REST with data formatted in JSON or XML.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The first version, SCIM 1.0, was released in 2011 by a SCIM standard working group organized under the Open Web Foundation.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] In 2011, it was transferred to the IETF, and the current standard, SCIM 2.0 was released as IETF RFC in 2015.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] SCIM 2.0 was completed in September 2015 and is published as IETF RFCs 7643 and 7644.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] A use-case document is also available as RFC 7642.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The standard has been implemented in various IdM software.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The standard was initially called ***Simple Cloud Identity Management*** (and is still called this in some places), but the name was officially changed to *System for Cross-domain Identity Management (SCIM)* when the IETF adopted it.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Interoperability was demonstrated in October, 2011, at the Cloud Identity Summit, an IAM industry conference.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] There, user accounts were provisioned and de-provisioned across separate systems using SCIM standards, by a collection of IdM software vendors: Okta, CyberArk, Ping Identity, SailPoint, Technology Nexus and UnboundID.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] In March 2012, at IETF 83 in Paris, interoperability tests continued by the same vendors, joined by Salesforce.com, BCPSoft, WSO2, Gluu, and Courion (now SecureAuth) nine companies in total.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] SCIM is the second standard for exchanging user data, but it builds on prior standards (e.g.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] SPML, PortableContacts, vCards, and LDAP directory services) in an attempt to be a simpler and more widely adopted solution for cloud services providers.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The SCIM standard is growing in popularity and has been adopted by numerous identity providers as well as applications.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] As adoption of the standard grows, so do the number of tools available.
[src:abac-access-control/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The standard leverages a number of open-source libraries to facilitate development and testing frameworks ensure that endpoint's compliance with the SCIM standard.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The **eXtensible Access Control Markup Language** (**XACML**) is an XML-based standard markup language for specifying access control policies.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The standard, published by OASIS, defines a declarative, fine-grained, attribute-based access control policy language, an architecture, and a processing model describing how to evaluate access requests according to the rules defined in policies.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] XACML is primarily an attribute-based access control policy language, but it also defines syntaxes for the requests sent by the Policy Enforcement Point to the Policy Decision Point, also called *authorization decision requests*.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The response process follows the aforementioned request flow in reverse.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] In XACML, attributes—information about the subject accessing a resource, the resource to be addressed, the action to be performed on the resource, and the environment—act as inputs deciding whether access is granted or not.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] XACML can also be used to implement role-based access control.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] In XACML, Rules specify the conditions under which an access request is approved (Permit) or rejected (Deny).
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] If a Rule is applicable to a request but the conditions within the Rule fail to evaluate, the result is Indeterminate.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Rules are grouped together in Policies and combined according to a combining algorithm defined by the parent Policy (e.g., deny-unless-permit, permit-unless-deny).
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Then, Policies may be grouped together in a larger Policy (or PolicySet in XACML 3.0) and combined according to its combining algorithm similarly.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Policies include a Target, which is a condition that determines whether that Policy should be evaluated for a given request.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Policies and Rules also include obligations and advice expressions.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Obligations specify actions that must be executed during the processing of a request (e.g., for logging).
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Advice expressions are similar but may be ignored.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] XACML separates access control functionality into several components.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Each operating environment in which access control is used has a Policy Enforcement Point (PEP), which implements the functionality to demand authorization and to grant or deny access to resources.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] These refer to an environment-independent and central Policy Decision Point (PDP), which is responsible for making the final access decision.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The PDP refers to policies stored in the Policy Retrieval Point (PRP).
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Policies are managed through a Policy Administration Point (PAP).
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] XACML 4.0 now has an equivalent representation in JSON: JACAL.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Version 1.0 was ratified by OASIS standards organization in 2003.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Version 2.0 was ratified by OASIS standards organization on February 1, 2005.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Version 3.0 was ratified by OASIS in January 2013 and updated in July 2017 (Version 3.0 Plus Errata 01).
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Version 4.0 (Committee Specification Draft 01) was published by OASIS in February 2026.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The PEP converts the request into a XACML authorization request.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The PEP forwards the authorization request to the Policy Decision Point (PDP).
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The PDP evaluates the authorization request against its configured policies.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The policies are acquired via a Policy Retrieval Point (PRP) and managed by a Policy Administration Point (PAP).
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] If needed, the PDP also retrieves attribute values from underlying Policy Information Points (PIP).
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The PDP reaches a decision (Permit, Deny, NotApplicable, or Indeterminate) and returns it to the PEP.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The PEP enforces the access decision against the user's request.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Up to XACML 3.0, a PolicySet can contain any number of PolicySet and/or Policy elements, and a Policy can contain any number of Rule elements.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] In XACML 4.0, a Policy can contain any number of Policy and/or Rule elements.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] There is no longer a distinction between Policy and PolicySet distinction.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Policies, Rules, and requests all use subjects, resources, environments, and actions.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] XACML provides a target, which is basically a condition about the attributes of the subject and/or resource and/or action and/or environment that must be met for a policy or rule to apply to a given request.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Once a policy is found to apply to a given request, its rules are evaluated to determine the access decision and response.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] In addition to being a way to check applicability, target information also provides a way to index policies, which is useful if you need to store many policies and then quickly sift through them to find which ones apply.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] When a request to access that service arrives, the PDP will know where to look for policies that might apply to this request because the policies are indexed based on their target constraints.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Note that a target may also specify that it applies to any request.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Policies and rules can all contain target elements.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Conditions are essentially boolean expressions that can use *AND, OR, NOT* operators and a broad range of functions that can be used to compare two or more attributes together, e.g. subject-id==doctor-id.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Up to XACML 3.0, Conditions are a more advanced form of Targets, whereas in XACML 4.0 they are the same.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] With conditions, it is possible to implement segregation of duty checks or relationship-based access control.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Within XACML, a concept called obligations can be used.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] An obligation is a directive from the policy decision point (PDP) to the policy enforcement point (PEP) on what must be carried out before or after an access is approved.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] If the PEP is unable to comply with the directive, the approved access *may* or *must* not be realized.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The augmentation of obligations eliminates a gap between formal requirements and policy enforcement.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The XACML's obligation can be an effective way to meet formal requirements (non-repudiation for example) that can be hard to implement as access control rules.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Furthermore, any formal requirements will be part of the access control policy as obligations and not as separate functions, which makes policies consistent and centralization of the IT environment easier to achieve.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Obligations can be used for "break-the-glass" scenarios or trust elevation ("you cannot transfer $1,000 without two-factor authentication - here is the link to the 2FA page").
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] In addition to obligations, XACML supports advice which are identical to obligations with the difference that a PEP is not obligated to enforce the advice (hence its name).
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] What happens in XACML if there are two rules (or policies) that contradict each other?
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Imagine for instance a first rule that would say *managers can view documents* and a second rule that would say *no one can work before 9am*.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] What if the request is about Alice trying to view a document at 8am?
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] This is what combining algorithms tell us.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] XACML defines a number of combining algorithms that can be identified by a *CombiningAlgId* attribute of the <Policy> (in XACML 4.0; or *PolicyCombiningAlgId* in XACML 3.0 <PolicySet> elements and *RuleCombiningAlgId* in <Policy> elements respectively).
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The combining algorithm of a policy *P* defines a procedure for combining the individual decision results of the rules and/or policies in *P* into one final access decision for *P*.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The functions and their identifiers are fully described in the standard.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Functions are type-specific i.e. there is a function for string equality and a different one for integer equality.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Refer to the standard for a formal definition of these function.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The list of higher order functions is as listed below.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] For a formal definition, refer to the XACML standard.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] XACML 3.0 introduces administrative delegation, the JSON Profile of XACML (request/response), the REST Profile of XACML, the Multiple Decision Profile of XACML, and many more.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The implementation of delegation is new in XACML 3.0.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The delegation mechanism is used to support decentralized administration of access policies.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] It allows an authority (delegator) to delegate all or parts of its own authority or someone else's authority to another user (delegate) without any need to involve modification of the root policy.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] This is because, in this delegation model, the delegation rights are separated from the access rights.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] These are instead referred to as administrative control policies.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] A partnership of companies' many services are protected by an access control system.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] When a consultant enters the corporation, a delegation can be issued locally by the consultant's supervisor, authorizing the consultant access to systems directly.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The delegator (the supervisor in this scenario) may only have the right to delegate a limited set of access rights to consultants.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] By default a PDP processes a single request at a time.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The PDP then replies with a single decision.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] At times, though, it is necessary to send multiple requests simultaneously.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The Multiple Decision Profile of XACML allows for this use case.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The PDP will typically return the product of all combinations in a single response.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] In 2013 and 2014, the XACML Technical Committee focused on designing new profiles to facilitate developer integration.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] All three profiles were showcased at the Cloud Identity Summit 2014 in Monterey, California.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Using these profiles, integrating fine-grained authorization into applications becomes much easier.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] In 2026, XACML 4.0 is released with major simplifications to the data and processing model, better support for JSON input data (with JSONPath profile), and the JACAL standard is released as a JSON syntax equivalent of XACML 4.0 for both policies and decision requests/responses.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] JACAL 1.0 is aligned with XACML 4.0 as it shares the same agnostic model ACAL.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] ALFA stands for Abbreviated Language for Authorization.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] It is a lightweight syntax used to implement policy-based access control policies.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The JSON profile of XACML simplifies the integration between the PEP and the PDP.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] XACML is almost entirely a **policy definition language** based on XML, defined by an open OASIS specification.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The XACML specification does not cover the design or implementation of Policy Decision Point (PDP), only the policy language they consume.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Many proprietary and open-source PDPs use XACML as their policy definition language.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] Open Policy Agent (OPA) is an open-source Policy Decision Point (PDP) implementation, capable of interpreting policy language to render policy decisions.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] OPA is a general-purpose PDP implementation which can be used for any scenario where a policy decision is required, much like PDP implementations that support the XACML specification.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] OPA's policy definition language is (Rego), which is a JSON-based, Turing-incomplete language based on Datalog.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] The project xacml-with-opa shows how to support the JSON Profile of XACML 3.0 with OPA.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] SAML is an identity SSO and federation standard used for authentication.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] SAML is used as a common identity token format between different applications.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] SAML and XACML are both defined by OASIS.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] SAML and XACML were designed to interoperate where SAML is used to carry identity information / virtual identities and XACML is used to drive the access control logic through policies.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] OAuth 2.0 is considered to be an authorization standard.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] It differs from XACML though in its origin, its purpose, and its applications.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] XACML does not handle user approval or delegated access or password management.
[src:abac-access-control/xacml] XACML and OAuth can be combined to deliver a more comprehensive approach to authorization.
